The pattern is grievance rewarded, not results delivered.What Coates really offers is a window into a mind shaped by anger, envy, and resentment. A man showered with praise and wealth should rejoice in the opportunities America provided and use his platform to inspire others. Instead, he insists that structural racism explains every hardship. He never considers alternative interpretations or the role of moral choices in shaping outcomes.Staying in school, avoiding drugs, marrying before having children ‚Äî these choices matter. The statistics are clear. None of them hinge on ‚Äústructural racism.‚ÄùKirk understood this. When confronted by students claiming that poverty forces crime, he rejected the premise. That view dehumanizes the poor, excuses immorality, and reduces human life to material conditions. Kirk countered with a vision rooted in responsibility, virtue, and perseverance.Coates, by contrast, repeats the falsehood that Kirk hated immigrants and LGBTQ people. He didn‚Äôt. He hated the sins that enslave people. He loved them as fellow humans and wanted them freed through Christ. He urged compliance with immigration laws not out of hate but out of respect for the rule of law ‚Äî the same standard applied to Americans abroad. These facts are easily verifiable if one is willing to look.The hypocrisy goes deeper. When Jimmy Kimmel was recently suspended, comedian Jim Gaffigan urged people to read his words directly rather than rely on secondhand distortions. Good advice. Why won‚Äôt the left follow it when it comes to Charlie Kirk? President Barack Obama claimed he never censored opponents, but his record shows otherwise. For decades, the left has policed speech, thought, and hiring.A grievance paradeCoates claims to fear that American history is being covered up. What he really fears is that his interpretation of history has been challenged and found wanting.He dwells on slavery but ignores the hundreds of thousands of young men who died to end it and the countless Christians who fought for abolition. He invokes Jim Crow and redlining but skips over the Democratic Party‚Äôs role in enforcing them. He wields ‚Äúracism‚Äù as a bludgeon against dissent. But that weapon has lost its power.RELATED: Joy Reid said the quiet part out loud ‚Äî and it‚Äôs ugly                                Photo by Eugene Gologursky/Getty Images for Fast CompanyAmerican history is human history ‚Äî the story of sinners, yes, but also of a nation shaped by Christians who proclaimed that true freedom comes only through Christ. Charlie Kirk preached that message. He affirmed the dignity of his opponents by debating them. He loved his country, he upheld its laws, he wanted its people to flourish ‚Äî but above all, he loved Christ and urged students to turn to Him as Savior.That is what we should remember. And that is what Coates cannot understand.

WHAT IS UNCUFFING AND WHY IS IT LINKED TO THE INCREASE IN SEPARATIONS IN SPRING? UNCUFFING REFERS TO THE PHENOMENON WHERE COUPLES WHO WERE PREVIOUSLY IN A LONG-TERM RELATIONSHIP OR EVEN MARRIED, SUDDENLY DECIDE TO BREAK UP OR SEPARATE, OFTEN IN THE SPRING SEASON. THIS PHENOMENON HAS BEEN OBSERVED IN VARIOUS CULTURES AND IS OFTEN ATTRIBUTED TO A COMBINATION OF FACTORS. IN THE SPRING, PEOPLE TEND TO FEEL A SENSE OF RENEWAL AND REJUVENATION, WHICH CAN LEAD TO A RE-EVALUATION OF THEIR RELATIONSHIPS. AS THE WEATHER WARMS UP AND PEOPLE BECOME MORE ACTIVE OUTDOORS, THEY MAY FEEL A DESIRE TO BREAK FREE FROM THE MONOTONY OF THEIR DAILY ROUTINES AND EXPLORE NEW EXPERIENCES AND CONNECTIONS. THIS CAN LEAD TO A SENSE OF RESTLESSNESS AND DISCONTENT IN RELATIONSHIPS THAT WERE PREVIOUSLY STABLE. ADDITIONALLY, THE SPRING SEASON OFTEN BRINGS NEW OPPORTUNITIES AND SOCIAL EVENTS, SUCH AS OUTDOOR GATHERINGS, FESTIVALS, AND VACATIONS, WHICH CAN PROVIDE A CATALYST FOR PEOPLE TO RE-EVALUATE THEIR RELATIONSHIPS AND POTENTIALLY SEEK NEW CONNECTIONS. THIS CAN BE ESPECIALLY TRUE FOR THOSE WHO WERE PREVIOUSLY IN A LONG-TERM RELATIONSHIP AND MAY HAVE BEEN FEELING STUCK OR STAGNANT. UNCUFFING CAN ALSO BE LINKED TO THE IDEA OF 'SPRING CLEANING,' WHERE PEOPLE FEEL THE NEED TO PURGE THEIR LIVES OF ANYTHING THAT IS NO LONGER SERVING THEM, INCLUDING UNHEALTHY OR UNFULFILLING RELATIONSHIPS. AS A RESULT, THE SPRING SEASON CAN BE A TIME OF SIGNIFICANT CHANGE AND TRANSFORMATION FOR MANY INDIVIDUALS, INCLUDING THOSE WHO MAY BE SEEKING A FRESH START OR A NEW CHAPTER IN THEIR LIVES.

I‚Äôve seen many Bitcoin maximalists debating whether to call it ‚Äútimechain‚Äù instead of ‚Äúblockchain‚Äù‚Äîmostly because ‚Äúblockchain‚Äù has become such a buzzword and is often misused.

As far as I‚Äôm concerned, I could also just call it ‚Äúchain‚Äù or, why not, ‚Äúsatschain.‚Äù

For me, the name doesn't change the fact that it‚Äôs a continuous chain of data‚Äîin practice, a chain of satoshi transactions‚Äîthat has a unique sense of time: one that emerges existentially from consensus and difficulty adjustments, not from scientific clocks.

So, whatever you call it, the core of Bitcoin remains the same: a protocol where time and truth are intertwined in a living network.

In the end, names are just labels; what truly matters is the temporal and Cartesian revolution that Bitcoin has brought to cyberspace, guaranteeing the second axis of knowledge and uniqueness on the Internet.
